04464nam a22005295i 9780674242029DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742420297 a10.4159/97806742420292doi  a(DE-B1597)534881  a(OCoLC)1117635201  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHC110.W4bB57 2019eb 7aBUS0690302bisacsh04a339.209732231 aBoushey, Heather, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnbound :bHow Inequality Constricts Our Economy and What We Can Do about It /cHeather Boushey. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI. HOW INEQUALITY OBSTRUCTS -- tII. HOW INEQUALITY SUBVERTS -- tIII. HOW INEQUALITY DISTORTS -- tConclusion: The Economic Imperative of Equitable Growth -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom one of Washington’s most influential voices on economic policy, a lively and original argument that reducing inequality is not just fair but also key to delivering broadly shared economic growth and stability. Do we have to choose between equality and prosperity? Many think that reducing economic inequality would require such heavy-handed interference with market forces that it would stifle economic growth. Heather Boushey, one of Washington’s most influential economic voices, insists nothing could be further from the truth. Presenting cutting-edge economics with journalistic verve, she shows how rising inequality has become a drag on growth and an impediment to a competitive United States marketplace for employers and employees alike. Boushey argues that inequality undermines growth in three ways. It obstructs the supply of talent, ideas, and capital as wealthy families monopolize the best educational, social, and economic opportunities. It also subverts private competition and public investment. Powerful corporations muscle competitors out of business, in the process costing consumers, suppressing wages, and hobbling innovation, while governments underfund key public goods that make the American Dream possible, from schools to transportation infrastructure to information and communication technology networks. Finally, it distorts consumer demand as stagnant wages and meager workplace benefits rob ordinary people of buying power and pushes the economy toward financial instability. Boushey makes this case with a clear, accessible tour of the best of contemporary economic research, while also injecting a passion for her subject gained through years of research into the economics of work–life conflict and policy work in the trenches of federal government. Unbound exposes deep problems in the U.S. economy, but its conclusion is optimistic. We can preserve the best of our nation’s economic and political traditions, and improve on them, by pursuing policies that reduce inequality—and by doing so, boost broadly shared economic growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCompetitionzUnited States. 0aElectronic books. 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 0aWealthzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065203140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424202940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674242029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674242029.jpg  a978-3-11-065203-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles